thread.title: Florida State wins sixth straight game over Miami with 29-24 victory
thread.title_full: Florida State wins sixth straight game over Miami with 29-24 victory

title: Florida State wins sixth straight game over Miami with 29-24 victory
text:
Florida State wins sixth straight game over Miami with 29-24 victory Safid Deen, Democrat staff writer 2:45 a.m. EDT October 11, 2015 Dalvin Cook runs in for his second rushing touchdown, third touchdown overall, and the go-ahead score against Miami at Doak Campbell Stadium on Saturday. (Photo: Joe Rondone/Democrat) 231 CONNECT 159 TWEET LINKEDIN COMMENT EMAIL MORE 
FINAL: The Florida State-Miami rivalry is alive and well. 
Unfortunately for the Hurricanes, it’s still a one-sided affair. 
FSU defensive lineman Giorgio Newberry batted down a fourth-down pass by Miami quarterback Brad Kaaya with under a minute left, and the Seminoles held on for a 29-24 victory on Saturday night. 
“When you create the right habits, good things happen,” FSU head coach Jimbo Fisher said. “And that’s what you saw tonight.” 
Kaaya torched Florida State’s defense, completing 29 of 49 passes for 405 yards and three touchdowns, but the second-year starter was unable to prevent the Seminoles from winning their sixth consecutive game in the series. Florida State coach Jimbo Fisher speaks to media after the Seminoles' 29-24 win over the Miami Hurricanes on Saturday, Oct. 11, 2015. Safid Deen/Democrat 
Florida State running back Dalvin Cook looked explosive in his return from a hamstring injury, accounting for 22 carries for 222 yards rushing and two touchdowns. He also had three catches for 47 yards and a receiving touchdown to lead the Seminoles in Doak Campbell Stadium in front of 82,329 people. 
“Dalvin Cook is one of the best pure players in college football,” Fisher said. “He had 222 yards on 22 carries and he wasn’t even supposed to play. .... That guy is something different. There’s something different in him, now.” 
Kicker Roberto Aguayo converted on three of four field goals, and quarterback Everett Golson completed 25 of 33 passes for 291 yards and a touchdown to carry FSU’s offense. FSU's Roberto Aguayo, two Miami players involved in pregame tussle 
The Seminoles (5-0, 3-0 Atlantic Coast Conference) have won 34 of their last 35 games. 
The Hurricanes (3-2, 0-1 ACC), who came into the game ranked 126th of 127 teams in the FBS on third down, fixed their troubles converting 8 of 16 third-down plays on the Seminoles defense. 
Starting cornerback Jalen Ramsey and safety Lamarcus Brutus each missed an opportunity during the game to pick off Kaaya, playing his second game in the rivalry. Photos: FSU versus Miami fan cam 
But with Miami’s backs against the wall on a game-deciding drive, the Seminoles defense answered the call to prevent a letdown after an impressive outing by FSU’s offense. 
Cook, with about 9 minutes left in the first half, came up lame after a 35-yard run with an open field in front of him, but returned to action. His first play back was an 18-yard gain up the middle, ending with a smile from the second-year running back. Florida State running back Dalvin Cook speaks to media after the Seminoles' 29-24 win over the Miami Hurricanes on Saturday, Oct. 11, 2015. Safid Deen/Democrat 
The Seminoles offense used several option plays to present a different look and get Golson more involved. 
His pitch to Cook in the first quarter resulted in a 72-yard touchdown run by Cook, and it seemed like the Seminoles were off to the races. 
FSU left points on the field, with Aguayo missing his first ever kick against the Hurricanes, a 49-yard attempt as halftime came to an end. 
Miami scored twice in the second half, with Kaaya connecting on a 1-yard pass to Cook’s high school teammate, running back Joe Yearby in the third quarter. 
Kaaya’s 29-yard pass to Stacy Coley gave UM its first lead of the game, 24-23 with more than 10 minutes remaining in the game.
